                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        <date>Dec 19_50</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Your esteemed favor of <date>15<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >th</hi></date> ins. was<lb/> handed to father
                                        with my manuscript by <persName>Mr. T. I.
                                        Seixas</persName><lb/> and should have had an earlier reply
                                        had I not<lb/> been desirous to give you the explanation so
                                                  asked<add>?</add> for<lb/> from <persName>Mr
                                                  Lyons</persName> relative to the publication of
                                                  <persName>Mr. Peynados</persName> letter<lb/> to
                                        the Presbyterian Synod, but altho' I am yet unable to
                                        furnish<lb/> the explanation you desire, I will no longer
                                        delay answering yours<lb/> lest you might attribute my
                                        silence to indifference to the<lb/> unmerited outrage
                                        inflicted by the Article of the Asmonean.<lb/> I had
                                        previously to receipt of your letter seen &amp; read,
                                        with<lb/> strong indignation at the foul &amp; scurrilous
                                        tone of the writer<lb/> and the petty malignancy of the
                                        temper which pervaded it. The<lb/> article signed with the
                                        initials of the senior Editor, and tho' I<lb/> felt the
                                        strongest desire to step forward in your
                                        <sic>defence</sic>,<lb/> I felt that the attack was so
                                        personal in its nature that you<lb/> alone, in this case,
                                        were the fitter champion of your own reputation.<lb/> I feel
                                        however all the delicacy of your position &amp;
                                        acknowledge<lb/> that a man whose public life has been
                                        passed in active efforts of usefulness<lb/>
                                        <del>and</del> to his coreligionists at large, <hi
                                                  rend="underline">and</hi> the value of whose
                                        services<lb/> has been so repeatedly acknowledged on all
                                        sides should not want<lb/> friends to step forward to
                                        protect him from scurrilous &amp; unmerited<lb/> abuse.
                                                  <persName>Mr. Schoval</persName> &amp; myself have
                                        both been earnestly<lb/> considering the matter and are only
                                        at a loss to know thro' what<lb/> channel we might be
                                        enabled to present our advocacy to the</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>public eye. The Asmonean will not admit, an antidote to its<lb/>
                                        own poison, malignant misconstruction might ascribe any
                                        article<lb/> in the Occident to the pen or dictation of its
                                        Editor, &amp; thought<lb/> of offering an article to the
                                        “Sunday Times” the Editor of which<lb/> has always professed
                                        the most friendly interest for your<lb/> welfare, &amp;
                                        respect for your character, But will he give currency<lb/>
                                        to what may tend to the disparagement &amp; infamy of a
                                        paper<lb/> of which his Son is associate Editor, but I see
                                        no remedy<lb/> but to test him. I shall prepare an article
                                        for the Times—<lb/> and <persName>Mr Schoal</persName> has
                                        promised to furnish one for the Occident,<lb/> with regard
                                        to <persName>Mr Peynados</persName> letter I called
                                        yestermorning at<lb/> the Sanctum of the Asmn. But found
                                        only the junior Editor to<lb/> whom in absence of his Senior
                                        I showed it, he thought it had been copied<lb/> from the
                                        Presbyterian, but on referring to the file found that the
                                        Editor<lb/> in a note referred to a private source from
                                        which he had derived it.<lb/> I left it with him to be
                                        handed <persName>Mr. S.</persName> with a promise that he
                                        should<lb/> by letter give the required explanation to
                                                  <persName>Mr Peynado</persName> &amp; that he
                                        would<lb/> likewise furnish me with one, but I am now near
                                        the close<lb/> of the second day and have not yet heard from
                                        him and think<lb/> it probable that he may feel too
                                        indifferent, to give himself the<lb/> trouble.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Isaac's</persName> apology was
                                        sufficiently lame &amp; not at all<lb/> in the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">terms</hi> in which he expressed
                                        himself to me on the subject<lb/> but it was at least an
                                        apology; doing you justice if not<lb/> himself</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have nothing of moment to add. All are well<lb/>
                                        and desire regards.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">Yours truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(11)">
                                        <persName role="author">E. Block</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
